^SAMPLE = GSM9494111
!Sample_title = Hepatocellular carcinoma, patient A-24, tissue adjacent to tumor, live and CD45-sorted
!Sample_geo_accession = GSM9494111
!Sample_status = Public on Feb 09 2026
!Sample_submission_date = Feb 04 2026
!Sample_last_update_date = Feb 09 2026
!Sample_type = SRA
!Sample_channel_count = 1
!Sample_source_name_ch1 = hepatocellular carcinoma
!Sample_organism_ch1 = Homo sapiens
!Sample_taxid_ch1 = 9606
!Sample_characteristics_ch1 = tissue: hepatocellular carcinoma
!Sample_molecule_ch1 = polyA RNA
!Sample_extract_protocol_ch1 = Tumor resection samples and adjacent liver tissue were digested in RPMI containing Collagenase I & II (0.1 mg/ml, Thermo Fisher Scientific) and DNAse I, minced, and digested for one hour using the GentleMACS system (Miltenyi Biotec). Isolation of live and CD45+ cells was performed using MACS LS columns (Miltenyi Biotec).
!Sample_extract_protocol_ch1 = Library was performed according to the manufacterâs instructions (single cell 10x 5â version 1 protocol, 10x Genomics). Briefly, cell suspensions were combined with master mix and loaded into the chip with gel beads to generate the gel bead-in-emulsion (GEM), which contains an Ilumina R1 primer sequence, Unique Molecular Identifier (UMI) and the 10x Barcode. Reverse transcription was performed on the poly-A RNA within each GEM. The pooled barcoded cDNA was then cleaned up with Silane DynaBeads and amplified by PCR. To prepare libraries from cDNA, SPRIselect beads were used to isolate the correct size fragments. Ilumina R2 primer sequence, paired-end constructs with P5 and P7 sequences, and a sample index were added during library construction.
!Sample_description = Library name: A-24-Adjacent-CD45+
!Sample_data_processing = CellRanger version 7.0.0 (10x Genomics, Genome Build: GRCh38 3.0.0) was used to align the raw sequencing data.
!Sample_data_processing = Doubletdetection to identify doublet cells from the single cell data. The scanpy data analysis pipeline was used for pre-processing and analysis of scRNAseq data, with the following software versions: scanpy 1.6.0, anndata 0.7.4, umap 0.4.1, numpy 1.19.1, scipy 1.5.2, pandas 1.1.2, scikit-learn 0.23.2, statsmodels 0.12.0, python-igraph 0.8.2, and louvain 0.8.2. Cells with less than 100 genes, greater than 2500 genes, or with >10% of genes being mitochondrial were removed. Additionally, platelets and red blood cells were also removed. We filtered out ribosomal and mitochondrial genes and genes detected in less than 3 cells. Gene counts were then normalized, log transformed, scaled, and corrected for batch effects. Principal component analysis was used to reduce the dimensionality of the dataset, and the top 50 principal components were used as input for clustering via the Leiden algorithm.
!Sample_data_processing = Assembly: GRCh38 3.0.0
!Sample_data_processing = Supplementary files format and content: Tab-separated values files and matrix files
